ce:section.ce:para:
The CPD@GO-3 substrate exhibits intactness and wrinkled surface as pristine GO (Fig. S1b, d). Transmission electron microscope (TEM) and high-resolution TEM (HRTEM) images (Fig. 1b, c) clearly show the CPDs in regular sphericity with average diameter of about 4.3 nm (
                           Fig. S3
                        ), and are uniformly distributed on GO flakes. Furthermore, CPDs possess high crystalline carbon with lattice spacing of 0.33 nm (Fig. 1c inset), resulting in favorable electrical conductivity for fast kinetic process. Noticeably, the agglomeration of the intrinsic characteristic of GO is highly weakened in the projected CPD@GO-3 substrate, because the in-situ formed CPDs effectively decrease the interlayer forces of GO flakes, thereby increasing GO layer spacing. Furthermore, the enlarged layer spacing of CPD@GO-3 is also proved by X-ray diffraction (XRD) pattern. From Fig. 1d, GO has a clear diffraction peak at about 10.1°, while this characteristic diffraction peak left shifted to 7.8°, and 5.5° for CPD@GO-1 and CPD@GO-3, respectively. The enlarged interlayer spacing not only improves Li+ transport kinetics between layers, but also effectively restricts the volume expansion of Li metal. For the CPD@GO-6, the diffraction peak of GO almost disappears, attributing to the reduction by the addition of a large amount of ammonia.

The CPD@GO-3 substrate possesses light weight (areal density of approximately 3.2 mg cm−2) and excellent flexibility and integrity. Even if it is folded many times (
                           Fig. S4
                        ), the structure is maintained as original state, indicating the significant practical application potential of CPD@GO-3 substrate in flexible LMBs with high energy density. SEM images of cross-side view show the average thickness of CPD@GO-3 film is ∼ 8 μm stacked by slightly crumpled 2D sheets (
                           Fig. S5
                        ), and some interlayer gaps that facilitate Li+ transport during cycling. The corresponding elements mapping further demonstrates the uniform distribution of C, N, and O on the whole substrate (
                           Fig. S6
                        ).

In order to identify the mass content of CPD anchored on the GO, the mass difference and element analysis (EA) were performed. According to the mass difference (
                           Table S3
                        ), the mass ratio of CPD is about 53.48 %. From the N content obtained by EA (
                           Table S4
                        ), the calculated mass content of CPD in the CPD@GO-3 is about 52.28 %, which is similar to that obtained from the mass difference.

Compared to RGO obtained through thermally reduced at 600 °C, GO and CPD@GO show much better flexibility because the graphene flexible bonds are not broken during the microwave reaction (
                           Fig. S8
                        ). To evaluate the energy barrier of heterogeneous nucleation, the nucleation overpotential of Li deposition on CPD@GO-3 and GO were investigated. According to the contact angle test (
                           Fig. S9
                        ), CPD@GO-3 has better wettability in electrolyte, which is conducive to mass transfer on the interface between electrolyte and electrode. First, CPD@GO-3 and GO electrode run 3 cycles at the range of 0.01–1 V. From the XRD results after cycling (

                           Fig. S10
                        ), the broader diffraction peak is attributed to the low graphitized carbon, suggesting in-situ electrochemical reduction from CPD@GO-3 and GO to CPD@RGO-3 and RGO occurs during the cycling process [44]. The reduction reactions improve the electronic conductivity of electrode (
                           Table S5
                        ). Second, nucleation overpotential is tested at different current density with a fixed capacity of 0.5 mAh cm−2. According to Fig. 2
                        a, the voltage drops to −0.0607 V in the initial process that Li plate on CPD@RGO-3, and the voltage platform reaches a stable value of −0.0424 V (vs. Li+/Li) after nucleation process. The nucleation overpotential is the difference between the bottom of voltage dip and the latter plateau voltage [45,46], so the nucleation overpotential of CPD@RGO-3 is calculated to be 18.3 mV at 1 mA cm−2. Likewise, the Li deposition voltage initially drops to −0.1165 V (vs. Li+/Li) and then gradually stabilizes at 0.0440 V (vs. Li+/Li) for RGO electrode, with the nucleation overpotential of 72.5 mV. When the current density increases to 2 and 5 mA cm−2 (
                           Fig. S11
                        ), the nucleation overpotential of Li plating is 22.3 and 44.2 mV for CPD@RGO-3, while it is 90.2 and 110 mV for RGO (Fig. 2b). CPD@RGO-3 displays lower nucleation overpotential, indicating the even distribution of lithiophilic sites from CPDs and feasible Li nucleus growth on CPD@RGO-3.

To evaluate the electrochemical performance, CE and galvanostatic profile of Li plating/stripping was tested. CE, an important parameter for evaluating the cycling stability of electrode, is the ratio of plating Li to stripping Li for substrates [47–49]. As shown in Fig. 2c, CPD@RGO-3 electrode maintains stable CE (∼96.0 %, >130 cycles) at 1 mA cm−2 with fixed capacity of 0.5 mAh cm−2. In contrast, the CE of RGO electrode is 89.7 % for the 70th cycle but declines rapidly during the later cycling at 1 mA cm−2. The CE results demonstrate CPD@RGO-3 electrodes keep highly reversible Li plating/stripping. For the CPD@RGO-1 and CPD@RGO-6 (
                           Fig. S12
                        ), due to the lack of nucleation sites and aggregation of CPDs, the CE performance does not improve significantly.

From Fig. 4c-e, the content of LiN3 and LiF is barely detected in the SEI layer on RGO surface, while Li2O/Li2CO3 is main component. In contrast, LiN3 and LiF are produced on the CPD@RGO-3 electrode surface, which indicates lithiophilic –NH2 and –COOH functional groups that promote the decomposition of LiTFSI salts [30]. LiN3 and LiF, with high chemical stability and ionic conductivity, can facilitate rapid Li+ transfer dynamics and suppress dendritic Li growth [51–54]. Moreover, comparing to the XPS data of CPD@RGO-1 (
                           Fig. S14

                        ) and CDP@RGO-3 (
                           Fig. S15

                        ), the results prove that the regulation of the suitable lithiophilic sites is more conducive to promote the generation of the stable SEI. The element mapping (
                           Fig. S16

                        ) also shows the well-dispersed N and F elements on the electrode surface, demonstrating high electrode/electrolyte interface stability.
